                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15894" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Sun, 1 Jan 2006 06:40:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Well, eventually that ClassLoader will only get passed down to the standard Class.forName(String, boolean, ClassLoader)  method - which determines the caller&apos;s class loader in case of a null argument. So I would expect the caller&apos;s class loader to be used if no thread context ClassLoader has been set...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16020" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 9 Jan 2006 01:00:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Any thoughts on this, Torsten? Is the caller&apos;s class loader not sufficient in this case, or doesn&apos;t it quite work as expected?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16025" author="torsten" created="Mon, 9 Jan 2006 07:53:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Passing a null ClassLoader to Class.forName(String, boolean, ClassLoader) doesn&apos;t use the caller&apos;s class loader (which would be fine in case of Eclipse). From the Java 1.5 API doc:&lt;br/&gt;
&quot;...&lt;br/&gt;
If the parameter &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;loader&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; is null, the class is loaded through the bootstrap class loader.&lt;br/&gt;
...&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The bootstrap class loader doesn&apos;t know anything about Eclipse&apos;s plugins and their dependencies.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I case of Spring IDE any class loader (the caller&apos;s or the one from ClassUtil) other than the bootstrap class loader would be fine. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Torsten&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16027" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 9 Jan 2006 09:17:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the clarification, Torsten. OK, we&apos;re using getDefaultClassLoader() there now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
